Creating the scATAC-seq data

This is tutorial is based on https://stuartlab.org/signac/articles/mouse_brain_vignette. Download the files from:

  • http://cf.10xgenomics.com/samples/cell-atac/1.1.0/atac_v1_adult_brain_fresh_5k/atac_v1_adult_brain_fresh_5k_filtered_peak_bc_matrix.h5
  • http://cf.10xgenomics.com/samples/cell-atac/1.1.0/atac_v1_adult_brain_fresh_5k/atac_v1_adult_brain_fresh_5k_fragments.tsv.gz
  • http://cf.10xgenomics.com/samples/cell-atac/1.1.0/atac_v1_adult_brain_fresh_5k/atac_v1_adult_brain_fresh_5k_fragments.tsv.gz.tbi
  • Youâll also need the atac_v1_adult_brain_fresh_5k_singlecell_kzl-updated.csv file created for this tutorial.

The following code is to create the Seurat object for snATAC-seq data. Notably, you need to use the Signac::CreateChromatinAssay() function, where you need to not only tell the function the count matrix counts, but also where the .tsv.gz file is. This is because Signac has functions that functions that require knowing specifically if thereâs a cut at any particular base pair (in the reference genome), not simply just how many cuts happen at a peak region. (The matrix counts, is simply a tally of how many cuts happen within a region, which is not high-resolution enough for some of the Signac functions.)

Note about wording: We will be using the words âchromatin regionâ and âpeakâ interchangeably.

setwd("/Users/kevinlin/Library/CloudStorage/Dropbox/Collaboration-and-People/sumie-katie/tutorial/sasc_2025/")

counts <- Seurat::Read10X_h5("atac_v1_adult_brain_fresh_5k_filtered_peak_bc_matrix.h5")
metadata <- read.csv(
  file = "atac_v1_adult_brain_fresh_5k_singlecell_kzl-updated.csv",
  header = TRUE,
  row.names = 1
)

seurat_atac <- Signac::CreateChromatinAssay(
  counts = counts,
  sep = c(":", "-"),
  genome = "mm10",
  fragments = 'atac_v1_adult_brain_fresh_5k_fragments.tsv.gz',
  min.cells = 1
)

# If you see this error: "Error: vector memory exhausted (limit reached?)"
# You can try `Sys.setenv(R_MAX_VSIZE = "100Gb")` beforehand

seurat_obj <- Seurat::CreateSeuratObject(
  counts = seurat_atac,
  assay = 'ATAC',
  meta.data = metadata
)

GenomeInfoDb::genome(annotations) <- "mm10"

# add the gene information to the object
Signac::Annotation(seurat_obj) <- annotations

Compute quality-control statistics

We now want to compute some quality-control statistics. One common one is Signac::NucleosomeSignal(). As you can see in https://stuartlab.org/signac/reference/nucleosomesignal and https://stuartlab.org/signac/articles/pbmc_vignette#computing-qc-metrics, this diagnostic uses the following logic: âThe histogram of DNA fragment sizes (determined from the paired-end sequencing reads) should exhibit a strong nucleosome banding pattern corresponding to the length of DNA wrapped around a single nucleosomeâ

seurat_obj <- Signac::NucleosomeSignal(seurat_obj)
seurat_obj$nucleosome_group <- ifelse(seurat_obj$nucleosome_signal > 4, 'NS > 4', 'NS < 4')
Signac::FragmentHistogram(seurat_obj, 
                          group.by = 'nucleosome_group', 
                          region = 'chr1-1-10000000')
#> Warning: Removed 1592 rows containing non-finite outside the scale range
#> (`stat_bin()`).
#> Warning: Removed 4 rows containing missing values or values outside the scale range
#> (`geom_bar()`).

Another is Signac::TSSEnrichment(). As you can see in https://stuartlab.org/signac/reference/tssenrichment and https://stuartlab.org/signac/articles/pbmc_vignette#computing-qc-metrics, this diagnostic uses the following logic: âThe ENCODE project has defined an ATAC-seq targeting score based on the ratio of fragments centered at the TSS to fragments in TSS-flanking regions. Poor ATAC-seq experiments typically will have a low TSS enrichment score.â

# the following line takes a couple minutes to run if you set "fast=FALSE"
## However, you'll need to set `fast=FALSE` in order to run the Signac::TSSPlot line
seurat_obj <- Signac::TSSEnrichment(seurat_obj,
                                    fast = FALSE)
#> Extracting TSS positions
#> Finding + strand cut sites
#> Finding - strand cut sites
#> Computing mean insertion frequency in flanking regions
#> Normalizing TSS score
# from https://stuartlab.org/signac/1.13.0/articles/pbmc_vignette
seurat_obj$high.tss <- ifelse(seurat_obj$TSS.enrichment > 3, 'High', 'Low')
Signac::TSSPlot(seurat_obj, group.by = 'high.tss') + Seurat::NoLegend()

Finally, there are âknownâ regions that consistently show abnormally high, unstructured, or irreproducible signal in sequencing assays. These are the âblacklistâ regions, we can also filter out cells that have too high counts in these regions. See more in https://stuartlab.org/signac/articles/pbmc_vignette#computing-qc-metrics.

seurat_obj$pct_reads_in_peaks <- seurat_obj$peak_region_fragments / seurat_obj$passed_filters * 100
seurat_obj$blacklist_ratio <- seurat_obj$blacklist_region_fragments / seurat_obj$peak_region_fragments

all_plots <- Seurat::VlnPlot(seurat_obj,
                             features = c('pct_reads_in_peaks', 
                                          'peak_region_fragments',
                                          'TSS.enrichment',
                                          'nucleosome_signal'),
                             ncol = 4)

Plotting

Now we want to visualize the remaining cells using a âtypicalâ pipeline. This involves using Signac::RunTFIDF() to perform a normalization, Signac::FindTopFeatures() to do a feature selection, and Signac::RunSVD() to perform a dimension reduction. (These are mathematically different from the analogous steps in scRNA-seq, which are typically log-normalization, variable gene selection based on the variance-stabilizing transform, and then PCA. However, conceptually, the steps here for scATAC-seq serve very similar purposes, just adapted for much sparser count data in scATAC-seq.)

Seurat::DefaultAssay(seurat_obj) <- "ATAC"

seurat_obj <- Signac::RunSVD(seurat_obj)

Compute gene activity scores

Since itâs often difficult to âinterpretâ chromatin regions (i.e., peaks), itâs sometimes convenient to âconvertâ the scATAC-seq data to be aligned with the genes. Signac::GeneActivity() achieves this, where essentially, it looks at the raw .tsv.gz file, and then checks for each geneâs TSS, how many cuts happen around that TSS. This essentially results in a matrix that has âgenesâ as features (instead of âpeaksâ). See more information in https://stuartlab.org/signac/reference/geneactivity. Be wary of the default: By default (currently, in Signac version 1.14.0), extend.upstream = 2000 and extend.downstream = 0, which means the cuts are defined as up to 2000 base pairs upstream of the TSS (on the 5â to 3â side, i.e., âbeforeâ the TSS), and not looking at any cuts after the TSS (downstream). See Figure 5 in https://academic.oup.com/bib/article/25/5/bbae382/7745032 to see that these numbers could be wildly different from method to method.

# compute gene activities
# This takes a couple minutes
gene_activities <- Signac::GeneActivity(seurat_obj)

# add the gene activity matrix to the Seurat object as a new assay
seurat_obj[['RNA']] <- Seurat::CreateAssayObject(counts = gene_activities)

seurat_obj <- Seurat::NormalizeData(
  object = seurat_obj,
  assay = 'RNA'
)

Making coverage plots

Since our data is scATAC-seq, we can plot the coverage track. This is a plot that looks like a mountain range, where for each stratification (typically, each cell type or cell cluster), we see across all the cells in that stratification, the average number of cuts that happened at that base pair region. See https://stuartlab.org/signac/reference/coverageplot for more information. If you dig into the code for this function, youâll see that the coverage track is a âdouble averageâ â first, for each cell, it averages the presence/absence of a cut at any particular base pair with its neighboring base pairs. Then, it averages this averaged cut count across all the cells in that stratification.

Seurat::Idents(seurat_obj) <- "predicted.id"
# show cell types with at least 50 cells
idents_plot <- names(which(table(Seurat::Idents(seurat_obj)) > 50))

idents_plot
#> [1] "Astro"   "L2/3 IT" "L4"      "L5 IT"   "L6 CT"   "L6 IT"
Seurat::DefaultAssay(seurat_obj) <- "ATAC"
Signac::CoveragePlot(
  object = seurat_obj,
  region = c("Neurod6"),
  idents = idents_plot,
  extend.upstream = 1000,
  extend.downstream = 1000,
  ncol = 1
)

Motif analysis using ChromVAR

Finally, we can do a motif analysis, see https://stuartlab.org/signac/articles/motif_vignette. This analysis answers the following question: âGiven that thereâs these peak regions, suppose thereâs some peak regions that are more accessible in one cell type than another. What are the transcription factors (TFs) that bind to these regions?â Answering this question might give us a clue on the regulatory mechanism on which transcription factors are more critical in one cell type when compared to another.

This analysis essentially needs a couple things:

    1. A database of the ATCG âsequenceâ that each transcription factor typically binds to. This is the âmotifâ, where you might have seen the position-weight matrices being visualized as âsequence logosâ before.
    1. A set of chromatin regions youâre interested in, and its underlying ATCG sequence along the DNA.

The following two code chunks gets these ingredients set up â first, use the JASPAR2020 package to assemble a set of TFs with their motifs, and put them into seurat_obj.

# Get a list of motif position frequency matrices from the JASPAR database
pfm <- TFBSTools::getMatrixSet(
  x = JASPAR2020,
  opts = list(collection = "CORE", tax_group = 'vertebrates', all_versions = FALSE)
)

# add motif information
# This takes a couple minutes 
seurat_obj <- Signac::AddMotifs(
  object = seurat_obj,
  genome = BSgenome.Mmusculus.UCSC.mm10,
  pfm = pfm
)
#> Building motif matrix
#> Finding motif positions
#> Creating Motif object

seurat_obj
#> An object of class Seurat 
#> 179011 features across 779 samples within 2 assays 
#> Active assay: ATAC (157203 features, 157203 variable features)
#>  2 layers present: counts, data
#>  1 other assay present: RNA
#>  2 dimensional reductions calculated: lsi, umap
da_peaks <- Seurat::FindMarkers(
  object = seurat_obj,
  ident.1 = 'L4',
  ident.2 = 'L2/3 IT',
  only.pos = TRUE, # This is an important parameter to set, for our interpretation to come
  test.use = 'LR',
  min.pct = 0.3, # changed to 0.2 just to make the calculation faster for this demo
  latent.vars = 'nCount_ATAC'
)

head(da_peaks)

# get top differentially accessible peaks
top_da_peak <- rownames(da_peaks[da_peaks$p_val < 0.005 & da_peaks$pct.1 > 0.2, ])
length(top_da_peak)

Finally, we can do the chromVAR analysis. This analysis asks: Given the nucleotide sequence (ATCG) of the chromatin regions of interest, are there certain TFs (based on their motifs) that could potentially bind more to these regions, when compared to all the other regions not being highlighted? (If you dig into the Signac::FindMotifs() code, it calls a method called chromVAR which has a dedicated sub-routine to find reasonable âbackground peaksâ that match the peaks of interest based on their regionâs basepair length, GC content, etc.). The end result is a p-value, one per motif, where a smaller p-value means that motif is more significantly enriched in the peaks of interest, relative to the background set of peaks.

# test enrichment
enriched_motifs <- Signac::FindMotifs(
  object = seurat_obj,
  features = top_da_peak
)
#> Selecting background regions to match input sequence characteristics
#> Matching GC.percent distribution
